  <li id="comment-41751" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/12758815889808936025" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">pvl</a></cite></div>
      <a href="index.html?p=241#comment-41751"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2013-11-23T18:41:11-05:00">Saturday, November 23, 2013 at 6:41 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>So, on the topic of salting the bean soaking water &#8230;</p>
<p>This confuses me a bit, I wonder if you would consider the science, and then wonder out loud why you&#39;ve had success with it?</p>
<p>My understanding &#8211; 2nd hand, but from reliable &#8220;sciency&#8221; food writers, is that when you salt the bean soaking liquid, the salt gets in the bean and then causes the bean to repel water &#8211; which has explained a period of time when EVERY SINGLE time I tried to make black bean-something-or-other the little buggers came out hard, no matter how long they soaked or cooked.</p>
<p>Since stopping the salting practice, I&#39;ve not had this issue.</p>
<p>But apparently this has not been your experience?</p>
<p>Discuss &#8230;</p>
<p>😉</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='index.html?p=241#comment-41751' data-commentid="41751" data-postid="241" data-belowelement="comment-41751" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to pvl" aria-label='Reply to pvl'>Reply</a>    </div>
